    "Commentary Vol. 102": "This is the disciple which testifieth of these things, etc.] Recorded\nin this chapter concerning the appearance of Christ to his disciples at the\nsea of Tiberias, and what were done by him in their presence, what passed\nbetween them; particularly the conversation he had with Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`, both\nconcerning himself, and the disciple John `[char_John_Ref]`: and also, of all things that are\nwritten in this whole Gospel. These are testified to be true by this very\ndisciple John `[char_John_Ref]`, concerning whom the above report went upon a mistaken\nsense of Christ\u2019s words, and who himself\nwrote these things; all that is contained in this book, as well as the\nparticulars relating to this conversation of Christ with Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]`:\nand we know that his testimony is true. The testimony of one that was an\neye and ear-witness, as John `[char_John_Ref]` was, of all that he testified and wrote, must be\nknown, owned, and allowed by all to be true, firm, and unquestionable; and\ntherefore the apostle speaks in the plural number, as being not only his own\nsense, but the sense of all men. Though some take this to be the attestation\nof the Ephesian church, or of the bishops of the Asiatic churches, who put\nJohn `[char_John_Ref]` upon writing this Gospel; of which they give their judgment and\ntestimony, as believing it to be a true and faithful narrative.\nVer.",
    "John Barton": ") even though Gen IT2I refers to only one covenant, the one that God promises to establish with Isaac, whom Sarah `[char_Sarah_Ref]` will bear to Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`. In fact Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` does not refer explicitly to the Sarah `[char_Sarah_Ref]` covenant, and does not even name her. Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` focuses on Hagar, who is said to come from Mount Sinai, a detail not mentioned in Genesis. Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`'s further comment about Hagar in\nv. 24). Implicit is the conviction that Christ is the image of the new humanity, the completion of God's purpose in creating humankind, and the template for the recreation of the old humanity into the new (cf 2:I5; 4:I3; Rom Ip4; Col po). The general exhortations which follow (vv. 25-32) focus particularly on personal relations and underline the import\u00ad ance of conversation, as a force for community building and as potentially destructive of community (cf Jas }:6-I2). They are based on age-old proverbial wisdom, familiar among both Greek and Jewish moralists, but of no less value for that. Members of a church (of one another) should be able to speak the truth to each other (\nv. 24); then immediately he says that he knows this with confidence (cf I:6, I9), for the Philippians' 'progress and joy in faith': (\nv. 24, Philemon is a fellow worker, apparently one who assists the imprisoned apostle."
